<br>
Re-reading that statement from Sanya gives me pause.  My interpretation of her statement is as follows...<br>
<br>
If you are engaged with a caster.  The attack speed has no influence on the ability ot interrupt.  The interrupt is a check of your engagement versus the casting of the spell.  It sounds like there is one check per cast per attacker to see if the spell goes off or if the caster is distracted and misses the spell.  It is independent of whether you swing every 5 sec or 1.5 sec.  The end point becomes (I am guessing) from whether the attacker kills the caster with a faster weapon before the 5 sec lands or not.<br>
<br>
So, to answer your question, I think if he has 3 casts per your swing, you can indeed interrupt all three casts before you land an attack. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#efe0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=svipdag@teamskald>Svipdag</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Participant</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#ff0000>(5/3/03 7:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=595.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Interrupt</span><hr size=1> Yes, it is possible to interrupt all of them. But I think the main difference between the slow and fast weapon is the following:<br>
